even under UP ("same time" in a<br />very limited sense, obviously - but one interrupt can interrupt the<br />other). As such, if we are ever in a critical section where this makes a<br />difference, that critical section obviously has to do a cli/sti.<br /><br />And they do. <br /><br />&gt; In any event, I think that the rtlinux soft-interrupts fits into this<br />&gt; scheme quite well and should make the irq_lock unecessary.<br /><br />I don't believe you can make the irq_lock unnecessary - _something_ like<br />that is needed anyway.<br /><br />		Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
